<%= faq_schema([
  { question: "How many pints per day do I need for a 1500 sq ft basement?", answer: "For moderately damp conditions (musty smell in humid weather) you need about 18 pints per day. For very damp (wet spots on walls) you need about 22 pints. For wet conditions (sweating walls, seepage) you need about 26 pints. For extremely wet (standing water) you need about 30 pints. Always round up to the next commercial size." },
  { question: "What is the difference between the old and new dehumidifier ratings?", answer: "Before 2019, dehumidifier capacity was tested at 80 °F and 60% RH. Since 2019, the DOE test uses a harsher 65 °F and 60% RH (closer to typical basement conditions). This dropped nameplate ratings by roughly 25%. A pre-2019 '70-pint' dehumidifier is approximately equivalent to a post-2019 '50-pint' unit. The calculator uses modern AHAM/ENERGY STAR values." },
  { question: "What humidity level should I target?", answer: "30-50% relative humidity is the EPA recommendation for comfortable and healthy indoor air. Below 30% causes dry skin, static electricity, and respiratory irritation. Above 50% supports mold, dust mites, and musty smells. Above 60% is where real damage occurs — wood rots, finishes peel, musty odors develop." },
  { question: "Where should I place a dehumidifier?", answer: "In the center of the room with at least 6 inches of clearance on all sides for airflow. Do not place against walls or in corners. For basements, set it on the floor (where moisture is highest) in the middle of the space. Run a condensate hose to a floor drain so you don't have to empty the tank daily. Clean the filter monthly." },
  { question: "Should I get one big dehumidifier or two smaller ones?", answer: "One larger unit is usually cheaper per pint of capacity and uses less total energy than two smaller ones. Exception: if the space has multiple rooms with walls or barriers, one unit per zone works better than trying to push moist air through doorways. A whole-house dehumidifier (70+ pints) ducted into HVAC returns is the most efficient for large homes." }
]) %>

